</span>

</figure>
<div data-type="example" id="fs-idp247735616">
<p id="fs-idp89066240"><span data-type="title">Calculating the Energy of an Electron in a Bohr Orbit</span>
Early researchers were very excited when they were able to predict the energy of an electron at a particular distance from the nucleus in a hydrogen atom. If a spark promotes the electron in a hydrogen atom into an orbit with <em data-effect="italics">n</em> = 3, what is the calculated energy, in joules, of the electron?</p>
<p id="fs-idp40593920"><span data-type="title">Solution</span>
The energy of the electron is given by this equation:</p>
<div data-type="equation" id="fs-idp20573264"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></div>
<p id="fs-idp4204032">The atomic number, <em data-effect="italics">Z</em>, of hydrogen is 1; <em data-effect="italics">k</em> = 2.179 <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>&#215;</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>&#215;</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/></annotation-xml></semantics></math> 10<sup>&#8211;18</sup> J; and the electron is characterized by an <em data-effect="italics">n</em> value of 3. Thus,</p>
<div data-type="equation" id="fs-idp199624080"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>2.179</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>&#215;</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>&#8722;18</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>J</mtext><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>&#215;</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>=</mo><mn>&#8722;2.421</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>&#215;</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>&#8722;19</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>J</mtext></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>2.179</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>&#215;</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>&#8722;18</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>J</mtext><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>&#215;</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>=</mo><mn>&#8722;2.421</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>&#215;</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>&#8722;19</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>J</mtext></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></div>
<p id="fs-idp16142080"><span data-type="title">Check Your Learning</span>
The electron in <a href="#CNX_Chem_06_02_BohrArrows" class="autogenerated-content">[link]</a> is promoted even further to an orbit with <em data-effect="italics">n</em> = 6. What is its new energy?</p>
<div data-type="note" id="fs-idp230904800"><div data-type="title">Answer:</div>
<p id="fs-idp107506336">&#8722;6.053 <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mo>&#215;</mo></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mo>&#215;</mo></annotation-xml></semantics></math> 10<sup>&#8211;20</sup> J</p></div>
</div>
